To print the string containing backslashes followed by `x9b`, which denotes an escaped octal byte (ASCII Bell), we must properly handle escaping within strings themselves as well. Here’s what this looks like in various languages:

Python example:
```python
# Including two levels of escapes because '\x' itself needs to be escaped inside a string literal
print("\\\x9b")
```

JavaScript example:
```javascript
// Again, double slashes are needed here due to JavaScript requiring them before any special character including those used for Unicode representation
console.log('\\\\x9b');
```

Java example:
```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Java uses forward slashes instead of backward ones but still requires doubling up each one
        System.out.println("\\/x9b");
    }
}
```

C++ example:
```cpp
int main() {
    std::cout << "\\\\x9b";
    return 0;
}
```

In all these cases, note that while printing out the actual code snippet might seem redundant given its simplicity, demonstrating proper quoting mechanisms across multiple languages emphasizes good practice regarding literals involving both regular and control characters such as newline (`\n`), tab (`\t`), etc., along with non-standard representations like octal codes indicated by prefixing `\`. This ensures clarity and maintainability especially when dealing with complex input parsing where raw inputs contain potentially harmful patterns. Always sanitize and validate external inputs rigorously to prevent security vulnerabilities associated with untrusted sources.

